<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Family at Falls of Clyde in New Lanark, Lanarkshire.jpg|thumb|Family at Falls of Clyde in New Lanark, Lanarkshire]] -->

'''The Lanarkshire Area Tourism Partnership''' (formerly Lanarkshire Strategic Tourism Marketing Partnership) created the strategy for tourism and [[economic development]] in [[Lanarkshire]] under the brand ''VisitLanarkshire'' in 2005.<ref name="news">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/7829344.stm|title=Tourism action plan boosts jobs|work=BBC News|date=15 January 2009}}</ref> This partnership is made up of representatives from [[North Lanarkshire]] and [[South Lanarkshire]] councils, [[VisitScotland]], and private organisations across Lanarkshire, and is funded by the Lanarkshire Tourism Association. The development of tourism is in line with the objectives set out in the Lanarkshire Tourism Action Plan.<ref name="visitscotland">{{cite web|url=http://www.visitscotland.org/what_we_do/partnership_initiatives/area_tourism_partnerships/lanarkshire.aspx|title=Lanarkshire Tourism Action Plan|publisher=VisitScotland|accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>

The [[partnership]]'s VisitLanarkshire initiative was introduced to support growth in the tourism sector, which has been higher than most other sectors in the local area<ref name="wishawpress">{{cite news|url=http://www.wishawpress.co.uk/wishaw-news/local-wishaw-news/wishaw-news/2009/11/25/lanarkshire-tourism-on-the-increase-76495-25241829/|title=Lanarkshire tourism on the increase |work=Wishaw Press|date=25 November 2009|first=Graham|last=Miller}}</ref> and makes a significant impact to Lanarkshire's [[economy]], attracting over 3 million [[Tourism|visitors]] a year and employing over 6,000 people.<ref name="visitscotland_a">{{cite web|url=http://www.visitscotland.org/research_and_statistics/regions/western_scotland.aspx|title=Scottish Tourism Economic Activity Monitor (STEAM) 2011|publisher=VisitScotland|accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref>

One of the partnership's main tasks is to manage local information through its dedicated website [http://www.visitlanarkshire.com www.visitlanarkshire.com], launched in 2009 <ref name="bbcnews">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/8392840.stm|title=Tourism bosses in Lanarkshire cash in on 'staycations'|work=BBC News|date=3 December 2009}}</ref> which is a [[database]] to help locals and tourists find information on towns, attractions, accommodation, news and events in Lanarkshire. This tool is useful as it helps 2,000 users a week to find information, and benefits in particular a local audience. [[Social media]] is another tool used to promote local events in the area to the public and to push seasonal marketing campaigns which provide visitor boosts in Spring and Autumn.

The partnership works in close contact with [[Lodging|accommodation]] providers and [[attractions]] in the area to maintain [[Requirement|standards]] set out by VisitScotland's quality grading schemes. Through the VisitLanarkshire name, the partnership also communicates the strategic aims set out by the ''Scottish Tourism Alliance'' to ensure its partners are working in parallel with the rest of [[Scotland]].

The partnership dedicated resources into producing a website promoting venues in Lanarkshire which was launched in 2012, after recognising that [[business tourism]] is a key growth sector in the tourism industry.

